You don't have the big herds of cattle and the great bands of sheep, of course, that you do in the West, but just the same, grazing and livestock production are mighty important to the farmers.
And you know, an interesting and very encouraging thing has been happening in recent years.
For a long time in the East and South, livestock were just turned loose into the woods to scrape up as much grass and other food as they could get.
Now, this didn't help the woods very much, especially where the hardwood trees grow, and it didn't help the livestock put on much weight either.
Well, what's been happening is the farmers have been going more and more into regular pastures, and

He that can make two blades of grass to grow upon a spot of ground where only one grew before deserves good of mankind and does essential service to his country.
The fellow who wrote that really knew what he was talking about because grass is much more than pretty green stuff growing on the range or in pastures.
It's food for the table, meat and milk and other dairy products.
It's leather for clothing and shoes and gloves.
and it's jobs for thousands of people.
